The paper deals with triangulating planar graphs, which is a topic in computational geometry (cs.CG) and graph theory (cs.DM). The problem of maintaining small pathwidth is a topic in graph algorithms (cs.DS) and graph theory (cs.GT). The techniques used in the paper involve dynamic programming and decomposition, which are common tools in algorithm design and analysis (cs.DS). Finally, the paper also discusses the application of the results to outer-planar graphs, which is a topic in graph theory and combinatorial optimization (cs.DM, cs.SI).
